 the man who would carry that name to a third generation: Beebe Hooker Strong, born Milwaukee 1866. He came to Wisconsin around 1830 at age ten, making the journey from the Rochester land grants his father had built to the Great Lakes frontier, and with him the Strong-Hooker legacy crossed into a new American West."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Edward Hooker, Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker (1909)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofrev00hook"},{"label":"History of Descendants of Elder John Strong, Vol. 1 (1871)","url":"https://dn720908.ca.archive.org/0/items/historyofdescend0001dwig/historyofdescend0001dwig.pdf"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"robert-strong-1820"},"I00916":{"id":"I00916","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Rosa","middle_name":"Searls","last_name":"Strong","maiden_name":"Warner","married_names":["Strong"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Rosa Searls Strong"},"birth":{"year":1823,"month":11,"day":5,"city":"Springfield","county":"Hampden County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1911,"month":7,"day":14,"city":"Chicago","county":"Cook County","state":"Illinois","country":"United States"},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM440","plot_notes":"Forest Home Cemetery Milwaukee per FA"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H02018","date_year":1859,"location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1892,"children_ids":["HD4626","HD4627","HD4628","HD4629","HD4632","HD4633"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Outlived her Milwaukee pioneer husband by nineteen years","body":"Rosa Searls Warner Strong, widowed when Robert Hunter Strong died at Waukesha in May 1892, lived on for nineteen more years — dying in Chicago on July 14, 1911 at age 87 while visiting her daughter, having outlasted her husband long enough to see her children established across three states. Her obituary noted that Robert had been instrumental in founding Forest Home Cemetery and that the family had been prominent at St. Paul's Episcopal Church — the church whose cemetery he helped build would ultimately receive them both."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave","url":"https://www.findagrave.com"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"rosa-warner-1823"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM445","name":"St. Anthony Cemetery","location":{"city":"Minneapolis","county":"Hennepin County","state":"Minnesota","country":"United States"},"url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/83249/st.-anthony-cemetery","hooker_connections":["I00925","HD4642","HD4644"]},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}